(44, 13, 27, 44, 15, 21, 21, 'read every sabbath day', 'Sabbath Readings and Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of readings from the prophets and Moses in synagogues every Sabbath. This connection highlights the continuity of scriptural teaching and its role in the community''s understanding of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 27, 45, 11, 25, 25, 'nor yet the voices of the prophets', 'Blindness and Fulfillment of Prophecy', 'This connection highlights the theme of blindness among Israel regarding the fulfillment of prophecies. Acts 13:27 mentions that the rulers did not know the voices of the prophets, while Romans 11:25 speaks of blindness in part happening to Israel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 27, 43, 15, 21, 21, NULL, 'Ignorance of God and Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance regarding God and His messengers. Both passages emphasize that those who oppose or condemn do so because they do not know Him or recognize His voice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 27, 45, 11, 8, 10, 'they knew him not', 'Spiritual Blindness and Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness in both passages. Acts 13:27 mentions the rulers'' failure to recognize Jesus, while Romans 11:8-10 describes God giving them a spirit of slumber, leading to their inability to see and hear.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 27, 46, 2, 8, 8, 'they knew him not', 'Ignorance of Rulers in Crucifixion', 'This connection highlights the ignorance of the rulers regarding Jesus'' identity. Both passages emphasize that had they known who He was, they would not have condemned or crucified Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 28, 40, 27, 22, 25, 'no cause of death in him', 'Connection of Innocence and Condemnation', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of evidence against Jesus, with Acts noting ''no cause of death in him'' and Matthew highlighting Pilate''s declaration of Jesus as ''this just person.'' This connection highlights the theme of wrongful condemnation despite recognized innocence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 28, 42, 23, 14, 16, 'no cause of death in him', 'Innocence of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of fault found in Jesus, highlighting that he was unjustly accused and condemned. Acts 13:28 states there was ''no cause of death in him,'' while Luke 23:14 confirms that both Pilate and Herod found ''no fault in this man.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 28, 42, 23, 21, 25, 'no cause of death in him', 'Connection of Innocence in Trials', 'Both passages emphasize that no cause of death was found in Jesus, highlighting the unjust nature of his condemnation. This repetition underscores the theme of innocence amidst the demands for crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 28, 43, 19, 4, 4, 'no cause of death in him', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence in both passages. Acts 13:28 states there was ''no cause of death in him,'' while John 19:4 emphasizes Pilate''s finding of ''no fault in him.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 28, 41, 15, 13, 15, 'found no cause of death in him', 'Connection of Innocence and Condemnation', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of evidence against Jesus, highlighting that he was delivered to be crucified despite no cause of death being found in him. This connection underscores the unjust nature of his condemnation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 28, 43, 18, 38, 38, 'no cause of death in him', 'Pilate''s Judgment of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s declaration of Jesus'' innocence. Acts 13:28 states there was ''no cause of death in him,'' while John 18:38 affirms, ''I find in him no fault at all.'' This connection highlights the consistent portrayal of Jesus'' lack of guilt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 28, 44, 3, 13, 14, 'desired they Pilate that he should be slain', 'Connection of Denial and Innocence', 'This connection highlights the theme of denial of Jesus'' innocence. Both passages emphasize that despite finding no cause for death, the crowd chose to reject Jesus and demand his execution.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 29, 42, 23, 53, 53, NULL, 'Burial of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying Jesus in a sepulchre after his crucifixion. This connection highlights the fulfillment of the narrative surrounding his death and burial.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 29, 43, 19, 28, 28, 'fulfilled all that was written of him', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the completion of what was written regarding Jesus. Acts 13:29 mentions fulfilling all that was written, while John 19:28 highlights that all things were now accomplished, indicating a shared theme of scriptural fulfillment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 29, 40, 27, 57, 60, 'laid him in a sepulchre', 'Burial of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking down Jesus'' body and laying it in a tomb. Acts 13:29 mentions laying him in a sepulchre, while Matthew 27:59-60 details Joseph wrapping and placing Jesus in his own tomb.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 29, 41, 15, 45, 46, 'laid him in a sepulchre', 'Connection of Burial Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking down Jesus'' body and laying it in a sepulchre. This connection highlights the fulfillment of the events surrounding Jesus'' death as described in Acts.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 29, 42, 24, 44, 44, 'fulfilled all that was written of him', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfillment in both passages. Acts 13:29 refers to the completion of what was written about Jesus, while Luke 24:44 emphasizes that all things must be fulfilled as written in the Scriptures concerning Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 29, 43, 19, 36, 42, 'laid him in a sepulchre', 'Fulfillment of Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of scripture regarding Jesus'' death and burial. Acts 13:29 mentions Jesus being laid in a sepulchre, while John 19:36-42 details the burial process and references specific prophecies fulfilled in his death.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 29, 44, 5, 30, 30, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the act of hanging Jesus on a tree, highlighting the fulfillment of what was written about him. This connection underscores the narrative of Jesus'' death and resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 30, 44, 2, 24, 24, 'God raised him from the dead', 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize God''s action in raising Jesus from the dead. Acts 13:30 states, ''God raised him from the dead,'' while Acts 2:24 elaborates on this by mentioning that God loosed the pains of death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 30, 44, 17, 31, 31, 'But God raised him from the dead:', 'Resurrection and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus as a pivotal event. Acts 13:30 states, ''But God raised him from the dead,'' which is foundational for the assurance of future judgment mentioned in Acts 17:31.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 30, 40, 28, 6, 6, NULL, 'Resurrection Announcement Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus. Acts 13:30 states, ''But God raised him from the dead,'' while Matthew 28:6 confirms, ''He is risen.'' This connection highlights the central theme of Jesus'' victory over death.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 30, 43, 2, 19, 19, 'raised him from the dead', 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection in both passages. Acts 13:30 states, ''God raised him from the dead,'' while John 2:19 mentions Jesus raising the temple in three days, indicating his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 30, 43, 10, 17, 17, 'raised him from the dead', 'Resurrection and Life Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the act of resurrection. Acts 13:30 states, ''God raised him from the dead,'' while John 10:17 speaks of taking life again, linking the concepts of death and resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 30, 58, 13, 20, 20, NULL, 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus, highlighting God''s role in bringing Him back from the dead. This connection underscores the significance of Jesus'' resurrection in the context of peace and the everlasting covenant.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 31, 42, 24, 48, 48, 'witnesses unto the people', 'Witnesses of Jesus'' Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of witnesses to Jesus'' ministry and resurrection. Acts 13:31 mentions those who witnessed Jesus, while Luke 24:48 directly addresses the disciples as witnesses of these events.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 31, 44, 1, 3, 3, 'seen many days of them', 'Witnesses of Christ''s Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the witnesses who saw Jesus after his resurrection. Acts 13:31 mentions those who were seen many days, while Acts 1:3 highlights that he was seen of them forty days.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
